 of changes in film industry practice, comedic tastes, and moviegoing culture. Each chapter is grounded in case studies of comedians and comic teams, including the Three Stooges, Laurel and Hardy, and Robert Benchley. The book also examines how the past legacy of silent-era slapstick was subsequently reimagined as part of a nostalgic mythology of Hollywood's youth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aComedy filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aComedy filmszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1920 american comedy.  a20th century comedians.  a20th century comedy teams.  acinematography.  acomedy films.  acomedy movies.  acomic movies.  adepression era film.  aearly 20th century cinema.  aearly sound era.  aearly sound slapstick.  afilm and tv.  afilm industry.  afilm studies.  ahistory of comedy.  ahistory of film.  ahokum.  alaurel and hardy.  amedia studies.  apopular culture.  arobert benchley.  asilent era slapstick.  aslapstick.  astage slang comedy.  athree stooges.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963160zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520963160.jpg  a978-3-11-066755-4 UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA